## 3. Prime Factorization: Breaking Down to Atoms

### History & the Fundamental Theorem

The *Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic* states: every integer greater than 1 is either prime, or can be written uniquely as a product of primes (ignoring order). 12 = 2 × 2 × 3. 60 = 2 × 2 × 3 × 5. This theorem is foundational—Euclid proved a version of it around 300 BCE, and it underpins all of number theory. Primes are the \"atoms\" from which all composite numbers are built.

### What We'll Do

Write a function to factor any number into its prime components, visualize the factorization as a tree, and recognize that this breakdown is always unique.

---

### Example 3.1: Trial Division—Finding One Prime Factor

To factor n, find the smallest prime that divides it.

```scheme
(define (smallest-prime-factor n)
  ;; Try every number from 2 upward until we find a divisor.
  (define (try d)
    (cond
      ((> (* d d) n) n)  ; n is prime
      ((= (modulo n d) 0) d)
      (else (try (+ d 1)))))
  (if (< n 2)
      'nan
      (try 2)))

(smallest-prime-factor 12)  ; 2
(smallest-prime-factor 35)  ; 5
(smallest-prime-factor 17)  ; 17 (itself)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print 2, 5, 17. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the smallest prime factors.]

---

### Example 3.2: Full Prime Factorization

Repeatedly divide out the smallest prime factor until we're left with 1.

```scheme
(define (prime-factors n)
  ;; Return a list of prime factors (with repetition).
  (define (loop n acc)
    (if (<= n 1)
        (reverse acc)
        (let ((p (smallest-prime-factor n)))
          (loop (/ n p) (cons p acc)))))
  (loop n '()))

(prime-factors 12)   ; (2 2 3)
(prime-factors 60)   ; (2 2 3 5)
(prime-factors 17)   ; (17)
(prime-factors 100)  ; (2 2 5 5)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the four factorizations. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing each factorization list.]

---

### Example 3.3: Prime Factorization with Exponents

Group repeated primes: 12 = 2² × 3¹.

```scheme
(define (prime-factorization n)
  ;; Return a list of (prime exponent) pairs.
  (define (group factors)
    (if (null? factors)
        '()
        (let* ((p (car factors))
               (rest (cdr factors))
               (same (filter (lambda (x) (= x p)) rest))
               (diff (filter (lambda (x) (not (= x p))) rest))
               (count (+ 1 (length same))))
          (cons (list p count) (group diff)))))
  (group (prime-factors n)))

(prime-factorization 12)
(prime-factorization 60)
(prime-factorization 128)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print ((2 2) (3 1)), ((2 2) (3 1) (5 1)), ((2 7)). -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing factorizations as (prime exponent) pairs.]

---

### Example 3.4: Reconstructing the Number from Its Prime Factorization

Given a list of (prime exponent) pairs, multiply them out.

```scheme
(define (from-prime-factorization pf)
  ;; pf is ((p1 e1) (p2 e2) ...)
  (fold (lambda (pair product)
          (* product (expt (car pair) (cadr pair))))
        1
        pf))

(from-prime-factorization '((2 2) (3 1)))  ; 12
(from-prime-factorization '((2 3) (5 2)))  ; 200
```

<!-- BUILD: Print 12 and 200. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the reconstructed numbers.]

---

### Example 3.5: Factor Tree as a Nested List

A factor tree splits a composite number into two factors, then recursively factors each until all leaves are prime.

```scheme
(define (factor-tree n)
  ;; Build a tree (n left right) or n if prime.
  (if (prime? n)
      n
      (let ((p (smallest-prime-factor n)))
        (list n (factor-tree p) (factor-tree (/ n p))))))

(factor-tree 12)
(factor-tree 60)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the nested lists: (12 2 (6 2 3)) and (60 2 (30 2 (15 3 5))). -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the nested-list representation of the trees. Below: a diagram of the 12 tree with 12 at top, splitting to 2 and 6, then 6 splitting to 2 and 3.]

---

### Example 3.6: Drawing the Factor Tree on Canvas (Conceptual)

We'll describe the structure—code will reference future plotting/tree-drawing verbs (which is fine; the *data* is ready).

```scheme
(define (factor-tree-positions n)
  ;; Assign (x, y) coordinates to each node in the tree.
  ;; For now, just return the tree and note positions will be computed.
  (let ((tree (factor-tree n)))
    (list 'tree tree 'note \"positions computed by layout algorithm\")))

(factor-tree-positions 60)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the tree structure and note. Actual drawing deferred to summit artifact. -->

[VISUAL: Describe—a binary tree laid out top-to-bottom, 60 at the top, branching to 2 and 30, then 30 to 2 and 15, then 15 to 3 and 5. Leaves are all prime.]

