## 5. Fraction Equivalence: The Role of Factors

### History & Reducing

Ancient Egyptians wrote fractions as sums of unit fractions (1/2, 1/3, 1/4…). The Babylonians used base-60 fractions (which is why we have 60 minutes in an hour). The modern fraction bar—numerator over denominator—emerged in medieval Europe. *Equivalent fractions* (1/2 = 2/4 = 3/6) are the same number written differently. Reducing a fraction means dividing numerator and denominator by their GCF, finding the simplest form.

### What We'll Do

Code fraction reduction, recognize equivalent fractions, and visualize them as shaded bars.

---

### Example 5.1: Reducing a Fraction to Lowest Terms

Divide numerator and denominator by their GCF.

```scheme
(define (reduce-fraction n d)
  ;; Return (n' d') in lowest terms.
  (let ((g (gcf n d)))
    (list (/ n g) (/ d g))))

(reduce-fraction 8 12)   ; (2 3)
(reduce-fraction 15 35)  ; (3 7)
(reduce-fraction 7 7)    ; (1 1)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print (2 3), (3 7), (1 1). -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the reduced fractions.]

---

### Example 5.2: Testing Fraction Equivalence

Two fractions are equivalent if their cross-products are equal: a/b = c/d iff a×d = b×c.

```scheme
(define (fractions-equal? a b c d)
  (= (* a d) (* b c)))

(fractions-equal? 1 2 2 4)  ; #t
(fractions-equal? 2 3 3 4)  ; #f
```

<!-- BUILD: Print #t and #f. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the boolean results.]

---

### Example 5.3: Listing Equivalent Fractions

Generate the first n equivalent fractions by multiplying numerator and denominator by 1, 2, 3, …

```scheme
(define (equivalent-fractions n d count)
  (map (lambda (k)
         (list (* k n) (* k d)))
       (iota count 1)))  ; iota count 1 = (1 2 3 ... count)

(equivalent-fractions 1 2 5)
(equivalent-fractions 2 3 4)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print ((1 2) (2 4) (3 6) (4 8) (5 10)) and ((2 3) (4 6) (6 9) (8 12)). -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the sequences of equivalent fractions.]

---

### Example 5.4: Visualizing Equivalent Fractions as Shaded Bars

Draw two bars—one divided into denominator-1 parts, one into denominator-2 parts—shade the same fraction of each.

```scheme
(define (fraction-bars n1 d1 n2 d2)
  ;; Return a structure describing two bars for plotting.
  (list (list 'bar-1 'parts d1 'shaded n1)
        (list 'bar-2 'parts d2 'shaded n2)))

(fraction-bars 1 2 2 4)
(fraction-bars 2 3 4 6)
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the bar descriptions. Rendering deferred to plot/ verbs. -->

[VISUAL: Two horizontal bars stacked vertically. Top bar: divided into 2 parts, 1 shaded (1/2). Bottom bar: divided into 4 parts, 2 shaded (2/4). Both show the same length shaded—visual proof of equivalence.]

---

### Example 5.5: Finding a Common Denominator

To add or compare fractions, convert them to a common denominator—often the LCM of the two denominators.

```scheme
(define (common-denominator a b c d)
  ;; Convert a/b and c/d to common denominator = lcm(b, d).
  (let* ((L (lcm b d))
         (a' (* a (/ L b)))
         (c' (* c (/ L d))))
    (list (list a' L) (list c' L))))

(common-denominator 1 2 1 3)  ; ((3 6) (2 6))
(common-denominator 2 5 3 7)  ; ((14 35) (15 35))
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the two pairs of equivalent fractions on common denominators. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the converted fractions.]

