## 6. Decimals: Division Continued

### History & Place Value

Decimals extend place value to the right of the ones place: tenths, hundredths, thousandths. Simon Stevin's 1585 pamphlet *De Thiende* (\"The Tenth\") popularized decimal fractions in Europe. A decimal is a fraction whose denominator is a power of 10: 0.25 = 25/100 = 1/4. Some fractions (1/2, 1/4, 1/5) terminate as decimals; others (1/3, 1/7) repeat forever.

### What We'll Do

Convert fractions to decimals, recognize terminating vs. repeating decimals, and round to a given number of places.

---

### Example 6.1: Fraction to Decimal (Terminating)

Divide numerator by denominator. If the denominator's only prime factors are 2 and 5, the decimal terminates.

```scheme
(define (fraction-to-decimal n d)
  (/ (* 1.0 n) d))

(fraction-to-decimal 1 2)   ; 0.5
(fraction-to-decimal 3 4)   ; 0.75
(fraction-to-decimal 7 8)   ; 0.875
```

<!-- BUILD: Print 0.5, 0.75, 0.875. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the decimal equivalents.]

---

### Example 6.2: Fraction to Decimal (Repeating)

1/3 = 0.333… The 3 repeats forever. Our float system will round after ~15 digits.

```scheme
(define (fraction-to-decimal-repeating n d)
  (/ (* 1.0 n) d))

(fraction-to-decimal-repeating 1 3)  ; 0.333...
(fraction-to-decimal-repeating 1 7)  ; 0.142857142857...
```

<!-- BUILD: Print the float approximations. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing 0.3333333333333333 and 0.14285714285714285.]

**Honest-null note:** Float arithmetic is approximate. For *exact* rational arithmetic, use the `exact/` namespace (coming soon in your curriculum). Here we're introducing decimals intuitively.

---

### Example 6.3: Rounding a Decimal to N Places

Use `math/round-to-place` (already wired).

```scheme
(define (round-decimal x places)
  (math/round-to-place x places))

(round-decimal 3.14159 2)   ; 3.14
(round-decimal 2.71828 3)   ; 2.718
```

<!-- BUILD: Print 3.14 and 2.718. -->

[VISUAL: Terminal output showing the rounded decimals.]

